</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">The pancreas is a retroperitoneal organ with a close anatomic relationship to the peritoneal reflections in the abdomen, including the transverse mesocolon and the small bowel mesentery, and is directly contiguous to peritoneal ligaments such as the hepatoduodenal ligament, gastrohepatic ligament, splenorenal ligament, gastrocolic ligament, and the greater omentum. Understanding of these anatomic relationships of the pancreas is aided by knowledge of its embryologic development. These reflections and ligaments are potential pathways for spread of disease processes such as pancreatitis and pancreatic carcinoma. One can recognize these ligaments and reflections by identifying the blood vessels that traverse them.</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.e34">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.e34">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F1" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e34/asset/images/g09mre34g01.jpeg" height="1280" width="1206" aria-labelledby="F1" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 1.</b>  The transverse mesocolon is formed by the fusion of the posterior leaf of the dorsal mesogastrium with the mesentery of the midgut. Hence, a direct contiguity is established between the transverse mesocolon and the greater omentum. <i>C</i> = colon. D= duodenum, <i>P</i> = pancreas, <i>S</i> = small intestine, <i>St</i> = stomach.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e34&amp;id=F1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F2" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e34/asset/images/g09mre34c02.jpeg" height="858" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F2" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 2.</b>  Frontal representation of the peritoneal ligaments and their relationships to the pancreas. <i>HDL</i> = hepatoduodenal ligament, <i>PCL</i> = phrenicocolic ligament, <i>SBM</i> = small bowel mesentery, <i>SRL</i> = splenorenal ligament, <i>TM</i> = transverse mesocolon.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e34&amp;id=F2">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F3" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e34/asset/images/g09mre34c03.jpeg" height="1119" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F3" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 3.</b>  Venous structures around the pancreas.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e34&amp;id=F3">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F4" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e34/asset/images/g09mre34c04.jpeg" height="1080" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F4" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 4.</b>  Arterial structures around the pancreas. <i>Lt</i> = left, <i>Rt</i> = right.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e34&amp;id=F4">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F5" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e34/asset/images/g09mre34g05x.jpeg" height="1236" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F5" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 5.</b>  Lateral illustration of the relationship of the pancreas (<i>P</i>) to the transverse mesocolon (<i>TM</i>) and small bowel mesentery (<i>SBM</i>). Disease processes can involve the transverse colon (<i>TC</i>) and the small bowel (<i>SB</i>) by spreading along this pathway (broken lines).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e34&amp;id=F5">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F6" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e34/asset/images/g09mre34g06x.jpeg" height="1144" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F6" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 6.</b>  Fluid along the transverse mesocolon secondary to pancreatitis. The long arrow indicates the middle colic vein. A plastic biliary stent (short arrow) is also seen. See <a href="http://radiographics.rsnajnls.org/cgi/content/full/e34/DC1">Movie 3</a>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e34&amp;id=F6">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F7" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e34/asset/images/g09mre34g07x.jpeg" height="1286" width="1350" aria-labelledby="F7" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 7.</b>  Pericolonic fat necrosis (arrows) secondary to pancreatitis, due to leakage of enzymes along the transverse mesocolon. See <a href="http://radiographics.rsnajnls.org/cgi/content/full/e34/DC1">Movie 3</a>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e34&amp;id=F7">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F8" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e34/asset/images/g09mre34g08.jpeg" height="1364" width="1476" aria-labelledby="F8" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 8.</b>  Computed tomographic scan shows carcinoma in the pancreatic head that extends along the transverse mesocolon, adjacent to the gastrocolic trunk (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e34&amp;id=F8">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F9" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e34/asset/images/g09mre34g09x.jpeg" height="1530" width="1530" aria-labelledby="F9" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 9.</b>  Pericolonic inflammation and thickening of the transverse colon (arrows) in a 57-year-old man with pancreatitis. Fluid is seen in the small bowel mesentery and the retroperitoneum around the right kidney (<i>r</i>). The head of the pancreas (<i>p</i>) is also demonstrated. See <a href="http://radiographics.rsnajnls.org/cgi/content/full/e34/DC1">Movie 3</a>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e34&amp;id=F9">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F10" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e34/asset/images/g09mre34g10.jpeg" height="1280" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F10" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 10.</b>  Pancreatitis has spread to the left transverse colon (white arrow). The left middle colic artery (black arrow) is the vascular landmark. See <a href="http://radiographics.rsnajnls.org/cgi/content/full/e34/DC1">Movie 3</a>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e34&amp;id=F10">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F11" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e34/asset/images/g09mre34g11.jpeg" height="1180" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F11" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 11.</b>  Fat necrosis (arrows) in the greater omentum in a 49-year-old man with pancreatitis.See <a href="http://radiographics.rsnajnls.org/cgi/content/full/e34/DC1">Movie 4</a>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e34&amp;id=F11">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F12" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e34/asset/images/g09mre34g12x.jpeg" height="1267" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F12" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 12.</b>  Axial-oblique maximum intensity projection image from a contrast-enhanced CT scan. The plane of the transverse mesocolon in relation to the head of the pancreas can be identified by following the marginal veins into the middle colic veins. The right middle colic vein usually drains into the gastrocolic trunk (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e34&amp;id=F12">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F13" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e34/asset/images/g09mre34g13.jpeg" height="645" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F13" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 13.</b>  Axial-oblique maximum intensity projection images at different levels from a contrast-enhanced CT scan.The plane is that of the transverse mesocolon. The left colic vein (arrow) drains into the inferior mesenteric vein (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e34&amp;id=F13">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F14" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e34/asset/images/g09mre34g14.jpeg" height="1206" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F14" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 14.</b>  Gastrosplenic and splenorenal ligaments in a patient with malignant ascites. The asterisk denotes fluid in the lesser sac. The posterolateral wall of the lesser sac is formed by the gastrosplenic ligament, which can be identified by recognizing the left gastroepiploic vessels (white arrow), and the splenorenal ligament, which houses the splenic artery and vein (black arrow) at the splenic hilum. The gastrosplenic ligament usually contains adipose tissue around the vessel, which in this patient has been replaced by tumor infiltration.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e34&amp;id=F14">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F15" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e34/asset/images/g09mre34g15.jpeg" height="1280" width="1216" aria-labelledby="F15" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 15.</b>  Pancreatitis in a 61-year-old woman. The pancreas is diffusely edematous (arrowheads). The disease extends to the gastrosplenic ligament (black arrow) via its direct contiguity with the splenorenal ligament at the splenic hilum. The gastrosplenic ligament is identified by identifying the left gastroepiploic vessels (white arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e34&amp;id=F15">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F16" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e34/asset/images/g09mre34g16.jpeg" height="1280" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F16" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 16.</b>  Pseudocyst formation in the splenorenal ligament (arrowheads). The splenic artery is displaced anteriorly (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e34&amp;id=F16">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F17" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e34/asset/images/g09mre34g17.jpeg" height="1280" width="1193" aria-labelledby="F17" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 17.</b>  Pancreatitis with thickening along the splenorenal ligament (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e34&amp;id=F17">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F18" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e34/asset/images/g09mre34g18.jpeg" height="1280" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F18" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 18.</b>  Axial oblique maximum-intensity projection shows the right gastric artery (white arrows) and the left gastric artery (black arrows) forming an anastomotic arcade in the gastrohepatic ligament.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e34&amp;id=F18">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F19" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e34/asset/images/g09mre34g19.jpeg" height="1280" width="1262" aria-labelledby="F19" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 19.</b>  Pancreatitis in a61-year-old woman with subperitoneal spread of inflammation (black arrows) around the left gastric artery (white arrow). The left gastric artery, as it travels superiorly in the retroperitoneum, raises a fold in the posterior layer of the peritoneum of the lesser sac to form the gastropancreatic fold.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e34&amp;id=F19">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F20" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e34/asset/images/g09mre34g20x.jpeg" height="1280" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F20" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 20.</b>  Pancreatic carcinoma growing into the gastrohepatic ligament (asterisk) in a 57-year-old woman. The right gastric artery (white arrows) and the left gastric artery (black arrows) serve as landmarks for identifying the ligament.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e34&amp;id=F20">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F21A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e34/asset/images/g09mre34g21a.jpeg" height="1280" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F21A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 21a.</b>  Axial maximum-intensity projections in a 64-year-old man with carcinoma of the head of the pancreas. <b>(a)</b> Tumor infiltrates the hepatoduodenal ligament (short white arrows). The hepatoduodenal ligament carries the proper hepatic artery (long white arrow), the portal vein (short black arrow), and the common bile duct. <b>(b)</b> Tumor is shown infiltrating the gastrohepatic ligament (short arrows). The anastomotic arcade of the right gastric artery and the left gastric artery (long arrow) serves as a landmark.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e34&amp;id=F21A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F21B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e34/asset/images/g09mre34g21b.jpeg" height="1280" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F21B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 21b.</b>  Axial maximum-intensity projections in a 64-year-old man with carcinoma of the head of the pancreas. <b>(a)</b> Tumor infiltrates the hepatoduodenal ligament (short white arrows). The hepatoduodenal ligament carries the proper hepatic artery (long white arrow), the portal vein (short black arrow), and the common bile duct. <b>(b)</b> Tumor is shown infiltrating the gastrohepatic ligament (short arrows). The anastomotic arcade of the right gastric artery and the left gastric artery (long arrow) serves as a landmark.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e34&amp;id=F21B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F22" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e34/asset/images/g09mre34g22.jpeg" height="1136" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F22" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 22.</b>  <b>P</b>seudocyst formation in the small bowel mesentery in a 38-year-old man. The small bowel mesentery can be identified by the jejunal artery and vein (arrows). See <a href="http://radiographics.rsnajnls.org/cgi/content/full/e34/DC1">Movie 5</a>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e34&amp;id=F22">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F23" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e34/asset/images/g09mre34g23x.jpeg" height="1154" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F23" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 23.</b>  Inflammation along the small bowel mesentery (arrows) secondary to pancreatitis in a 63-year-old man.See <a href="http://radiographics.rsnajnls.org/cgi/content/full/e34/DC1">Movie 5</a>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e34&amp;id=F23">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F24" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e34/asset/images/g09mre34g24x.jpeg" height="1280" width="1200" aria-labelledby="F24" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 24.</b>  Carcinoma of the head of the pancreas infiltrating inferiorly along the small bowel mesentery into the ileocolic mesentery (white arrows) in a 70-year-old woman. This structure is identified by the ileocolic artery (black arrow) and vein. See <a href="http://radiographics.rsnajnls.org/cgi/content/full/e34/DC1">Movie 5</a>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e34&amp;id=F24">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F25" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e34/asset/images/g09mre34g25x.jpeg" height="1239" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F25" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 25.</b>  Carcinoma of the head of the pancreas involving the jejunal mesentery (short arrows) in a 57-year-old man. The jejunal artery and vein (long arrow) serve as vascular landmarks to identify this structure. See <a href="http://radiographics.rsnajnls.org/cgi/content/full/e34/DC1">Movie 5</a>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e34&amp;id=F25">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F26" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e34/asset/images/g09mre34g26x.jpeg" height="1183" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F26" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 26.</b>  Fifty-nine-year-old woman with carcinoma of the head of the pancreas involving the uncinate process and infiltrating the base of the jejunal mesentery (white arrows) posterior to the jejunal vein (black arrow), a tributary of the superior mesenteric vein. See <a href="http://radiographics.rsnajnls.org/cgi/content/full/e34/DC1">Movie 5</a>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.e34&amp;id=F26">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="T1" class="table"><figcaption><b>Table 1.</b> <b>Derivatives of the Ventral and Dorsal Mesenteries</b></figcaption><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e34/asset/images/g09mre34t01xnew.jpeg" height="776" width="1800" aria-labelledby="T1" loading="lazy" /></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="T2" class="table"><figcaption><b>Table 2.</b> <b>Summary of Ligamentous Relationships and their Vascular Landmarks</b></figcaption><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.e34/asset/images/g09mre34t02xnew.jpeg" height="1550" width="1800" aria-labelledby="T2" loading="lazy" /></figure></div><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="R1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content"><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-firstauthor"><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-snm">Meyers</span><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-fnm">MA</span></span>, Evans JA. Effects of pancreatitis on the small bowel and colon: spread along mesenteric planes. <em>Am J Roentgenol Radium Ther Nucl Med</em>1973; 119: 151–165.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.2214/ajr.119.1.151">C